# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: greenplum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] In computing, a **data warehouse** (**DW** or **DWH**), also known as an **enterprise data warehouse** (**EDW**), is a system used for reporting and data analysis and is a core component of business intelligence.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are central repositories of data integrated from disparate sources.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] They store current and historical data organized in a way that is optimized for data analysis, generation of reports, and developing insights across the integrated data.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] They are intended to be used by analysts and managers to help make organizational decisions.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The data stored in the warehouse is uploaded from operational systems (such as marketing or sales).
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The data may pass through an operational data store and may require data cleansing for additional operations to ensure data quality before it is used in the data warehouse for reporting.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The two main workflows for building a data warehouse system are extract, transform, load (ETL) and extract, load, transform (ELT).
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Operational databases are optimized for the preservation of data integrity and speed of recording of business transactions through use of database normalization and an entity–relationship model.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Operational system designers generally follow database normalization to ensure data integrity.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Fully normalized database designs often result in information from a business transaction being stored in dozens to hundreds of tables.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Relational databases are efficient at managing the relationships between these tables.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The databases have very fast insert/update performance because only a small amount of data in those tables is affected by each transaction.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] To improve performance, older data are periodically purged.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are optimized for analytic access patterns, which usually involve selecting specific fields rather than all fields as is common in operational databases.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Because of these differences in access, operational databases (loosely, OLTP) benefit from the use of a row-oriented database management system (DBMS), whereas analytics databases (loosely, OLAP) benefit from the use of a column-oriented DBMS.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Operational systems maintain a snapshot of the business, while warehouses maintain historic data through ETL processes that periodically migrate data from the operational systems to the warehouse.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Online analytical processing (OLAP) is characterized by a low rate of transactions and complex queries that involve aggregations.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Response time is an effective performance measure of OLAP systems.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] OLAP applications are widely used for data mining.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] OLAP databases store aggregated, historical data in multi-dimensional schemas (usually star schemas).
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] OLAP systems typically have a data latency of a few hours, while data mart latency is closer to one day.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The OLAP approach is used to analyze multidimensional data from multiple sources and perspectives.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The three basic operations in OLAP are roll-up (consolidation), drill-down, and slicing & dicing.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Online transaction processing (OLTP) is characterized by a large numbers of short online transactions (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE).
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] OLTP systems emphasize fast query processing and maintaining data integrity in multi-access environments.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] For OLTP systems, performance is the number of transactions per second.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] OLTP databases contain detailed and current data.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The schema used to store transactional databases is the entity model (usually 3NF).
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Normalization is the norm for data modeling techniques in this system.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Predictive analytics is about finding and quantifying hidden patterns in the data using complex mathematical models to prepare for different future outcomes, including demand for products, and make better decisions.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] By contrast, OLAP focuses on historical data analysis and is reactive.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Predictive systems are also used for customer relationship management (CRM).
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] A Database is an organized collection of data that is stored and managed electronically.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] It is designed to store, retrieve and manage structured data using a DBMS(Database Management Software) for querying and manipulating the data.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] A data mart is a simple data warehouse focused on a single subject or functional area.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Hence it draws data from a limited number of sources such as sales, finance or marketing.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Data marts are often built and controlled by a single department in an organization.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The sources could be internal operational systems, a central data warehouse, or external data.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Types of data marts include dependent, independent, and hybrid data marts.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] A Data lake is a centralized repository that stores large volume of data in raw format that is processed at the run time.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] It can collect data from multiple sources such as APIs, Files, databases, sensors, websites, etc.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Unlike data warehouses, data lakes stores data is structured, semi-structured and unstructured format that makes them usable for machine learning and big data processing.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The typical extract, transform, load (ETL)-based data warehouse uses staging, data integration, and access layers to house its key functions.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The staging layer or staging database stores raw data extracted from each of the disparate source data systems.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The integration layer integrates disparate data sets by transforming the data from the staging layer, often storing this transformed data in an operational data store (ODS) database.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The integrated data are then moved to yet another database, often called the data warehouse database, where the data is arranged into hierarchical groups, often called dimensions, and into facts and aggregate facts.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The combination of facts and dimensions is sometimes called a star schema.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The access layer helps users retrieve data.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The main source of the data is cleansed, transformed, catalogued, and made available for use by managers and other business professionals for data mining, online analytical processing, market research and decision support.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] However, the means to retrieve and analyze data, to extract, transform, and load data, and to manage the data dictionary are also considered essential components of a data warehousing system.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Many references to data warehousing use this broader context.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Thus, an expanded definition of data warehousing includes business intelligence tools, tools to extract, transform, and load data into the repository, and tools to manage and retrieve metadata.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] ELT-based data warehousing gets rid of a separate ETL tool for data transformation.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Instead, it maintains a staging area inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] In this approach, data gets extracted from heterogeneous source systems and are then directly loaded into the data warehouse, before any transformation occurs.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] All necessary transformations are then handled inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Finally, the manipulated data gets loaded into target tables in the same data warehouse.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] A data warehouse maintains a copy of information from the source transaction systems.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The concept of data warehousing dates back to the late 1980s when IBM researchers Barry Devlin and Paul Murphy developed the "business data warehouse".
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] In essence, the data warehousing concept was intended to provide an architectural model for the flow of data from operational systems to decision support environments.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The concept attempted to address the various problems associated with this flow, mainly the high costs associated with it.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] In the absence of a data warehousing architecture, an enormous amount of redundancy was required to support multiple decision support environments.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] In larger corporations, it was typical for multiple decision support environments to operate independently.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Though each environment served different users, they often required much of the same stored data.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The process of gathering, cleaning and integrating data from various sources, usually from long-term existing operational systems (usually referred to as legacy systems), was typically in part replicated for each environment.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Moreover, the operational systems were frequently reexamined as new decision support requirements emerged.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Often new requirements necessitated gathering, cleaning and integrating new data from "data marts" that was tailored for ready access by users.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Additionally, with the publication of The IRM Imperative (Wiley & Sons, 1991) by James M.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Kerr, the idea of managing and putting a dollar value on an organization's data resources and then reporting that value as an asset on a balance sheet became popular.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] In the book, Kerr described a way to populate subject-area databases from data derived from transaction-driven systems to create a storage area where summary data could be further leveraged to inform executive decision-making.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] This concept served to promote further thinking of how a data warehouse could be developed and managed in a practical way within any enterprise.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] A fact is a value or measurement in the system being managed.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Raw facts are ones reported by the reporting entity.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Raw facts are aggregated to higher levels in various dimensions to extract information more relevant to the service or business.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] These are called aggregated facts or summaries.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] For example, if there are three BTSs in a city, then the facts above can be aggregated to the city level in the network dimension.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The two most important approaches to store data in a warehouse are dimensional and normalized.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The dimensional approach uses a star schema as proposed by Ralph Kimball.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The normalized approach, also called the third normal form (3NF) is an entity-relational normalized model proposed by Bill Inmon.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] In a dimensional approach, transaction data is partitioned into "facts", which are usually numeric transaction data, and "dimensions", which are the reference information that gives context to the facts.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] This dimensional approach makes data easier to understand and speeds up data retrieval.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Dimensional structures are easy for business users to understand because the structure is divided into measurements/facts and context/dimensions.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Facts are related to the organization's business processes and operational system, and dimensions are the context about them (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Another advantage is that the dimensional model does not involve a relational database every time.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Thus, this type of modeling technique is very useful for end-user queries in data warehouse.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The model of facts and dimensions can also be understood as a data cube, where dimensions are the categorical coordinates in a multi-dimensional cube, the fact is a value corresponding to the coordinates.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] It is difficult to modify the warehouse structure if the organization changes the way it does business.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] In the normalized approach, the data in the warehouse are stored following, to a degree, database normalization rules.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Normalized relational database tables are grouped into *subject areas* (for example, customers, products and finance).
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] When used in large enterprises, the result is dozens of tables linked by a web of joins.(Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The main advantage of this approach is that it is straightforward to add information into the database.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Disadvantages include that, because of the large number of tables, it can be difficult for users to join data from different sources into meaningful information and access the information without a precise understanding of the date sources and the data structure of the data warehouse.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Both normalized and dimensional models can be represented in entity–relationship diagrams because both contain joined relational tables.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The difference between them is the degree of normalization.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] These approaches are not mutually exclusive, and there are other approaches.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Dimensional approaches can involve normalizing data to a degree (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] In *Information-Driven Business*, Robert Hillard compares the two approaches based on the information needs of the business problem.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] He concludes that normalized models hold far more information than their dimensional equivalents (even when the same fields are used in both models) but at the cost of usability.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The technique measures information quantity in terms of information entropy and usability in terms of the Small Worlds data transformation measure.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] In the *bottom-up* approach, data marts are first created to provide reporting and analytical capabilities for specific business processes.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] These data marts can then be integrated to create a comprehensive data warehouse.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The data warehouse bus architecture is primarily an implementation of "the bus", a collection of confirmed dimensions and confirmed facts, which are dimensions that are shared (in a specific way) between facts in two or more data marts.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The *top-down* approach is designed using a normalized enterprise data model.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] "Atomic" data, that is, data at the greatest level of detail, are stored in the data warehouse.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Dimensional data marts containing data needed for specific business processes or specific departments are created from the data warehouse.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Data warehouses often use a spoke–hub distribution paradigm.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Legacy systems feeding the warehouse often include customer relationship management and enterprise resource planning, generating large amounts of data.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] To consolidate these various data models and facilitate the extract transform load process, data warehouses often make use of an operational data store, the information from which is parsed into the actual data warehouse.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] To reduce data redundancy, larger systems often store the data in a normalized way.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Data marts for specific reports can then be built on top of the data warehouse.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] A hybrid (also called ensemble) data warehouse database is kept on third normal form to eliminate data redundancy.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] A normal relational database, however, is not efficient for business intelligence reports where dimensional modelling is prevalent.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Small data marts can shop for data from the consolidated warehouse and use the filtered, specific data for the fact tables and dimensions required.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The data warehouse provides a single source of information from which the data marts can read, providing a wide range of business information.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The hybrid architecture allows a data warehouse to be replaced with a master data management repository where operational (not static) information could reside.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The data vault modeling components follow hub and spokes architecture.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] This modeling style is a hybrid design, consisting of the best practices from both third normal form and star schema.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The data vault model is not a true third normal form, and breaks some of its rules, but it is a top-down architecture with a bottom up design.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The data vault model is geared to be strictly a data warehouse.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] It is not geared to be end-user accessible, which, when built, still requires the use of a data mart or star schema-based release area for business purposes.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] There are basic features that define the data in the data warehouse that include subject orientation, data integration, time-variant, nonvolatile data, and data granularity.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Unlike the operational systems, the data in the data warehouse revolves around the subjects of the enterprise.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Subject orientation is not database normalization.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Subject orientation can be really useful for decision-making.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Gathering the required objects is called subject-oriented.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The data found within the data warehouse is integrated.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Since it comes from several operational systems, all inconsistencies must be removed.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Consistencies include naming conventions, measurement of variables, encoding structures, physical attributes of data, and so forth.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] While operational systems reflect current values as they support day-to-day operations, data warehouse data represents a long time horizon (up to 10 years) which means it stores mostly historical data.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] It is mainly meant for data mining and forecasting.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The data in the data warehouse is read-only, which means it cannot be updated, created, or deleted (unless there is a regulatory or statutory obligation to do so).
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] In the data warehouse process, data can be aggregated in data marts at different levels of abstraction.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The user may start looking at the total sale units of a product in an entire region.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Then the user looks at the states in that region.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Finally, they may examine the individual stores in a certain state.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Therefore, typically, the analysis starts at a higher level and drills down to lower levels of details.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources creating a virtual data warehouse.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The different methods used to construct/organize a data warehouse specified by an organization are numerous.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] The hardware utilized, software created and data resources specifically required for the correct functionality of a data warehouse are the main components of the data warehouse architecture.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] All data warehouses have multiple phases in which the requirements of the organization are modified and fine-tuned.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Data warehouses in this stage of evolution are updated on a regular time cycle (usually daily, weekly or monthly) from the operational systems and the data is stored in an integrated reporting-oriented database.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] Data warehouses at this stage are updated from data in the operational systems on a regular basis and the data warehouse data are stored in a data structure designed to facilitate reporting.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] These data warehouses assemble data from different areas of business, so users can look up the information they need across other systems.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] In the healthcare sector, data warehouses are critical components of health informatics, enabling the integration, storage, and analysis of large volumes of clinical, administrative, and operational data.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] These systems consolidate information from disparate sources such as electronic health records (EHRs), laboratory information systems, picture archiving and communication systems (PACS), and medical billing platforms.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] By centralizing data, healthcare data warehouses support a range of functions including population health, clinical decision support, quality improvement, public health surveillance, and medical research.
[src:greenplum/data-warehouse] These warehouses enable data-driven healthcare by supporting retrospective studies, comparative effectiveness research, and predictive analytics, often with the use of healthcare-applied artificial intelligence.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Starting in 2012, its database management system software became known as the **Pivotal Greenplum Database** sold through Pivotal Software.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Pivotal open sourced the core engine and continued its development by the Greenplum Database open source community and Pivotal.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Starting in 2020 Pivotal was acquired by VMware and VMware continued to sponsor the Greenplum Database open source community as well as commercialize the technology under the brand name **VMware Tanzu Greenplum**.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] In November 2023, VMware was acquired by Broadcom.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] In May 2024, Tanzu by Broadcom made the decision to close source the Greenplum Database project.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] All future releases of Greenplum Database will be closed source and released as part of the VMware Tanzu Data Suite.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Greenplum, the company, was founded in September 2003 by Scott Yara and Luke Lonergan.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] It was a merger of two smaller companies: Metapa (founded in August 2000 near Los Angeles) and Didera in Fairfax, Virginia.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Investors included SoundView Ventures, Hudson Ventures and Royal Wulff Ventures.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] A total of US$20 million in funding was announced at the merger.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Greenplum, based in San Mateo, California, released its database management system software based on PostgreSQL in April 2005 calling it Bizgres.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Rounds of venture capital of about US$15 million each were invested in March 2006 and February 2007.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] In July 2006 a partnership with Sun Microsystems was announced.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Sun, which had also acquired MySQL AB, participated in a round of US$27 million investment in January 2009, led by Meritech Capital Partners.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] The Bizgres project included a few other members, and was supported through about 2008, when the product was just called "Greenplum" as well.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] The Sun Fire X4500 was a reference architecture and used by the majority of customers until a transition was made to Linux around that time.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Greenplum was acquired by EMC Corporation in July 2010, becoming the foundation of EMC's big data software division.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Although EMC did not disclose the value, it was estimated at US$300 million.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Greenplum's products at the time of acquisition were the Greenplum Database, Chorus (a management tool), and Data Science Labs.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Greenplum had customers in vertical markets including eBay.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] It became part of Pivotal Software in 2012.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] A variant using Apache Hadoop to store data in the Hadoop file system called Hawq was announced in 2013.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] In 2015 the GreenplumDB and Hawq open source software projects were announced.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] The Greenplum database product uses massively parallel processing (MPP) techniques.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Each computer cluster consists of a master node, standby master node, and segment nodes.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] All of the data resides on the segment nodes and the catalog information is stored in the master nodes.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Segment nodes run one or more segments, which are modified PostgreSQL database instances and are assigned a content identifier.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] For each table the data is divided among the segment nodes based on the distribution column keys specified by the user in the data definition language.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] For each segment content identifier there is both a primary segment and mirror segment which are not running on the same physical host.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] When a query enters the master node, it is parsed, planned and dispatched to all of the segments to execute the query plan and either return the requested data or insert the result of the query into a database table.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] The Structured Query Language, version SQL:2003, is used to present queries to the system.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Transaction semantics comply with constraints known as ACID.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Competitors include other MPP database management systems provided by major vendors such as Teradata, Amazon Redshift, Microsoft Azure, Alibaba AnalyticDB and, in the past, IBM Netezza.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Additional competition comes from other smaller competitors, column-oriented databases such as HP Vertica, Exasol and data warehousing vendors with non MPP architecture, such as Oracle Exadata, IBM Db2 and SAP HANA.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] In September 2023, Greenplum Database Version 7 was released.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Version 7 is based on PostgreSQL version 12.12.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] In September 2019, Greenplum Database Version 6 was released.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Version 6 is based on PostgreSQL version 9.4 and features massive gains in OLTP performance.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] In September 2017, Greenplum Database Version 5 was released.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Version 5 includes the first iteration of the Greenplum project strategy of merging PostgreSQL later versions back into Greenplum and is based on PostgreSQL version 8.3 up from the previous version 8.2.
[src:greenplum/greenplum] Version 5 also introducing the General Availability of the GPORCA Optimizer for cost based optimization of SQL designed for big data.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] This repository was archived by the owner on May 24, 2024.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Greenplum Database (GPDB) is an advanced, fully featured, open source data warehouse, based on PostgreSQL.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] It provides powerful and rapid analytics on petabyte scale data volumes.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Uniquely geared toward big data analytics, Greenplum Database is powered by the world’s most advanced cost-based query optimizer delivering high analytical query performance on large data volumes.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] The Greenplum project is released under the Apache 2 license.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] We want to thank all our past and present community contributors and are really interested in all new potential contributions.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] For the Greenplum Database community no contribution is too small, we encourage all types of contributions.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] A Greenplum cluster consists of a **coordinator** server, and multiple **segment** servers.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] All user data resides in the segments, the coordinator contains only metadata.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] The coordinator server, and all the segments, share the same schema.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Users always connect to the coordinator server, which divides up the query into fragments that are executed in the segments, and collects the results.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] More information can be found on the project website.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] GPORCA is a cost-based optimizer which is used by Greenplum Database in conjunction with the PostgreSQL planner.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] It is also known as just ORCA, and Pivotal Optimizer.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] The code for GPORCA resides src/backend/gporca.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] The directory, the TCP ports, the number of segments, and the existence of standbys for segments and coordinator for the demo cluster can be changed on the fly.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Currently, GPDB is built with GPORCA by default.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] If you want to build GPDB without GPORCA, configure requires `--disable-orca` flag to be set.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] See Building GPDB client tools on Windows for details.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] There is a Vagrant-based quickstart guide for developers.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] The directory layout of the repository follows the same general layout as upstream PostgreSQL.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Greenplum is maintained by a core team of developers with commit rights to the main gpdb repository on GitHub.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] At the same time, we are very eager to receive contributions from anybody in the wider Greenplum community.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] This section covers all you need to know if you want to see your code or documentation changes be added to Greenplum and appear in the future releases.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Greenplum is developed on GitHub, and anybody wishing to contribute to it will have to have a GitHub account and be familiar with Git tools and workflow.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] It is also recommend that you follow the developer's mailing list since some of the contributions may generate more detailed discussions there.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Once you have your GitHub account, fork this repository so that you can have your private copy to start hacking on and to use as source of pull requests.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Anybody contributing to Greenplum has to be covered by either the Corporate or the Individual Contributor License Agreement.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] If you have not previously done so, please fill out and submit the Contributor License Agreement.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Note that we do allow for really trivial changes to be contributed without a CLA if they fall under the rubric of obvious fixes.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] However, since our GitHub workflow checks for CLA by default you may find it easier to submit one instead of claiming an "obvious fix" exception.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] If the contribution you're submitting is original work, you can assume that Pivotal will release it as part of an overall Greenplum release available to the downstream consumers under the Apache License, Version 2.0.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] However, in addition to that, Pivotal may also decide to release it under a different license (such as PostgreSQL License to the upstream consumers that require it.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] A typical example here would be Pivotal upstreaming your contribution back to PostgreSQL community (which can be done either verbatim or your contribution being upstreamed as part of the larger changeset).
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] If the contribution you're submitting is NOT original work you have to indicate the name of the license and also make sure that it is similar in terms to the Apache License 2.0.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Apache Software Foundation maintains a list of these licenses under Category A.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] In addition to that, you may be required to make proper attribution in the NOTICE file similar to these examples.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Finally, keep in mind that it is NEVER a good idea to remove licensing headers from the work that is not your original one.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Even if you are using parts of the file that originally had a licensing header at the top you should err on the side of preserving it.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] As always, if you are not quite sure about the licensing implications of your contributions, feel free to reach out to us on the developer mailing list.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Your chances of getting feedback and seeing your code merged into the project greatly depend on how granular your changes are.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] If you happen to have a bigger change in mind, we highly recommend engaging on the developer's mailing list first and sharing your proposal with us before you spend a lot of time writing code.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Even when your proposal gets validated by the community, we still recommend doing the actual work as a series of small, self-contained commits.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] This makes the reviewer's job much easier and increases the timeliness of feedback.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] When it comes to C and C++ parts of Greenplum, we try to follow PostgreSQL Coding Conventions.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] We recommend using `git diff --color` when reviewing your changes so that you don't have any spurious whitespace issues in the code that you submit.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] All new functionality that is contributed to Greenplum should be covered by regression tests that are contributed alongside it.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] If you are uncertain on how to test or document your work, please raise the question on the gpdb-dev mailing list and the developer community will do its best to help you.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] At the very minimum you should always be running `make installcheck-world` to make sure that you're not breaking anything.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] If the change you're working on touches functionality that is common between PostgreSQL and Greenplum, you may be asked to forward-port it to PostgreSQL.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] This is not only so that we keep reducing the delta between the two projects, but also so that any change that is relevant to PostgreSQL can benefit from a much broader review of the upstream PostgreSQL community.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] In general, it is a good idea to keep both code bases handy so you can be sure whether your changes may need to be forward-ported.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] To improve the odds of the right discussion of your patch or idea happening, pay attention to what the community work cycle is.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] For example, if you send in a brand new idea in the beta phase of a release, we may defer review or target its inclusion for a later version.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Feel free to ask on the mailing list to learn more about the Greenplum release policy and timing.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Once you are ready to share your work with the Greenplum core team and the rest of the Greenplum community, you should push all the commits to a branch in your own repository forked from the official Greenplum and send us a pull request.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] We welcome submissions which are work in-progress in order to get feedback early in the development process.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] When opening the pull request, select "Draft" in the dropdown menu when creating the PR to clearly mark the intent of the pull request.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Prefixing the title with "WIP:" is also good practice.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] All new features should be submitted against the main branch.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Bugfixes should too be submitted against main unless they only exist in a supported back-branch.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] If the bug exists in both main and back-branches, explain this in the PR description.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Once you submit your pull request, you will immediately see a number of validation checks performed by our automated CI pipelines.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] There also will be a CLA check telling you whether your CLA was recognized.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] If any of these checks fails, you will need to update your pull request to take care of the issue.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Pull requests with failed validation checks are very unlikely to receive any further peer review from the community members.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Keep in mind that the most common reason for a failed CLA check is a mismatch between an email on file and an email recorded in the commits submitted as part of the pull request.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] If you cannot figure out why a certain validation check failed, feel free to ask on the developer's mailing list, but make sure to include a direct link to a pull request in your email.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] A submitted pull request with passing validation checks is assumed to be available for peer review.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Peer review is the process that ensures that contributions to Greenplum are of high quality and align well with the road map and community expectations.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Every member of the Greenplum community is encouraged to review pull requests and provide feedback.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Since you don't have to be a core team member to be able to do that, we recommend following a stream of pull reviews to anybody who's interested in becoming a long-term contributor to Greenplum.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] As Linus would say "given enough eyeballs, all bugs are shallow".
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] One outcome of the peer review could be a consensus that you need to modify your pull request in certain ways.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] GitHub allows you to push additional commits into a branch from which a pull request was sent.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Those additional commits will be then visible to all of the reviewers.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] A peer review converges when it receives at least one +1 and no -1s votes from the participants.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] At that point you should expect one of the core team members to pull your changes into the project.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Greenplum prides itself on being a collaborative, consensus-driven environment.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] We do not believe in vetoes and any -1 vote casted as part of the peer review has to have a detailed technical explanation of what's wrong with the change.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] Should a strong disagreement arise it may be advisable to take the matter onto the mailing list since it allows for a more natural flow of the conversation.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] At any time during the patch review, you may experience delays based on the availability of reviewers and core team members.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] That being said, don't get discouraged either.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] If you're not getting expected feedback for a few days add a comment asking for updates on the pull request itself or send an email to the mailing list.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] On occasion you will see core team members committing directly to the repository without going through the pull request workflow.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] This is reserved for small changes only and the rule of thumb we use is this: if the change touches any functionality that may result in a test failure, then it has to go through a pull request workflow.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] If, on the other hand, the change is in the non-functional part of the code base (such as fixing a typo inside of a comment block) core team members can decide to just commit to the repository directly.
[src:greenplum/main-readme-md] For Greenplum Database documentation, please check the online documentation.
[src:greenplum/massively-parallel-processing] One approach is grid computing, where the processing power of many computers in distributed, diverse administrative domains is opportunistically used whenever a computer is available.
[src:greenplum/massively-parallel-processing] An example is BOINC, a volunteer-based, opportunistic grid system, whereby the grid provides power only on a best effort basis.
[src:greenplum/massively-parallel-processing] Another approach is grouping many processors in close proximity to each other, as in a computer cluster.
[src:greenplum/massively-parallel-processing] In such a centralized system the speed and flexibility of the interconnect becomes very important, and modern supercomputers have used various approaches ranging from enhanced InfiniBand systems to three-dimensional torus interconnects.
[src:greenplum/massively-parallel-processing] The term also applies to massively parallel processor arrays (MPPAs), a type of integrated circuit with an array of hundreds or thousands of central processing units (CPUs) and random-access memory (RAM) banks.
[src:greenplum/massively-parallel-processing] These processors pass work to one another through a reconfigurable interconnect of channels.
[src:greenplum/massively-parallel-processing] By harnessing many processors working in parallel, an MPPA chip can accomplish more demanding tasks than conventional chips.
[src:greenplum/massively-parallel-processing] MPPAs are based on a software parallel programming model for developing high-performance embedded system applications.
[src:greenplum/massively-parallel-processing] Goodyear MPP was an early implementation of a massively parallel computer architecture.
[src:greenplum/massively-parallel-processing] MPP architectures are the second most common supercomputer implementations after clusters, as of November 2013.
[src:greenplum/massively-parallel-processing] Data warehouse appliances such as Teradata, Netezza or Microsoft's PDW commonly implement an MPP architecture to handle the processing of very large amounts of data in parallel.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The PostgreSQL Global Development Group focuses only on developing a database engine and closely related components.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] This core is, technically, what comprises PostgreSQL itself, but there is an extensive developer community and ecosystem that provides other important feature sets that might, traditionally, be provided by a proprietary software vendor.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] These include special-purpose database engine features, like those needed to support a geospatial or temporal database or features which emulate other database products.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Also available from third parties are a wide variety of user and machine interface features, such as graphical user interfaces or load balancing and high availability toolsets.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The large third-party PostgreSQL support network of people, companies, products, and projects, even though not part of The PostgreSQL Development Group, are essential to the PostgreSQL database engine's adoption and use and make up the PostgreSQL ecosystem writ large.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL was originally named POSTGRES, referring to its origins as a successor to the Ingres database developed at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] In 1996, the project was renamed PostgreSQL to reflect its support for SQL.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] After a review in 2007, the development team decided to keep the name PostgreSQL and the alias Postgres.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL evolved from the Ingres project at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] In 1982, the leader of the Ingres team, Michael Stonebraker, left Berkeley to make a proprietary version of Ingres.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] He returned to Berkeley in 1985, and began a post-Ingres project to address the problems with contemporary database systems that had become increasingly clear during the early 1980s.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] He won the Turing Award in 2014 for these and other projects, and techniques pioneered in them.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The new project, POSTGRES, aimed to add the fewest features needed to completely support data types.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] These features included the ability to define types and to fully describe relationships – something used widely, but maintained entirely by the user.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] In POSTGRES, the database understood relationships, and could retrieve information in related tables in a natural way using *rules*.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] POSTGRES used many of the ideas of Ingres, but not its code.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Starting in 1986, published papers described the basis of the system, and a prototype version was shown at the 1988 ACM SIGMOD Conference.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The team released version 1 to a small number of users in June 1989, followed by version 2 with a re-written rules system in June 1990.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Version 3, released in 1991, again re-wrote the rules system, and added support for multiple storage managers and an improved query engine.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] By 1993, the number of users began to overwhelm the project with requests for support and features.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] After releasing version 4.2 on June 30, 1994 – primarily a cleanup – the project ended.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Berkeley released POSTGRES under an MIT License variant, which enabled other developers to use the code for any use.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] At the time, POSTGRES used an Ingres-influenced POSTQUEL query language interpreter, which could be interactively used with a console application named monitor.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] In 1994, Berkeley graduate students Andrew Yu and Jolly Chen replaced the POSTQUEL query language interpreter with one for the SQL query language, creating Postgres95.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The monitor console was also replaced by psql.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Yu and Chen announced the first version (0.01) to beta testers on May 5, 1995.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Version 1.0 of Postgres95 was announced on September 5, 1995, with a more liberal license that enabled the software to be freely modifiable.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] On July 8, 1996, Marc Fournier at Hub.org Networking Services provided the first non-university development server for the open-source development effort.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] With the participation of Bruce Momjian and Vadim B.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Mikheev, work began to stabilize the code inherited from Berkeley.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] In 1996, the project was renamed to PostgreSQL to reflect its support for SQL.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The online presence at the website PostgreSQL.org began on October 22, 1996.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The first PostgreSQL release formed version 6.0 on January 29, 1997.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Since then developers and volunteers around the world have maintained the software as The PostgreSQL Global Development Group.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The project continues to make releases available under its free and open-source software PostgreSQL License.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Code comes from contributions from proprietary vendors, support companies, and open-source programmers.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] As of 2025, PostgreSQL is on major release version 18 which is notable in implementing asynchronous I/O (AIO), enabling database users to perform concurrent I/O tasks like readahead and sequential scan.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL manages concurrency through multiversion concurrency control (MVCC), which gives each transaction a "snapshot" of the database, allowing changes to be made without affecting other transactions.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] This largely eliminates the need for read locks, and ensures the database maintains ACID principles.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL offers four levels of transaction isolation: Read Uncommitted, Read Committed, Repeatable Read and Serializable.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Because PostgreSQL is immune to dirty reads, requesting a Read Uncommitted transaction isolation level provides read committed instead.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL supports full serializability via the serializable snapshot isolation (SSI) method.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The PostgreSQL MVCC implementation is prone to performance issues that require tuning when under a heavy write load which updates existing rows.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in binary replication based on shipping the changes (write-ahead logs (WAL)) to replica nodes asynchronously, with the ability to run read-only queries against these replicated nodes.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] This allows splitting read traffic among multiple nodes efficiently.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Earlier replication software that allowed similar read scaling normally relied on adding replication triggers to the master, increasing load.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in synchronous replication that ensures that, for each write transaction, the master waits until at least one replica node has written the data to its transaction log.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Unlike other database systems, the durability of a transaction (whether it is asynchronous or synchronous) can be specified per-database, per-user, per-session or even per-transaction.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] This can be useful for workloads that do not require such guarantees, and may not be wanted for all data as it slows down performance due to the requirement of the confirmation of the transaction reaching the synchronous standby.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Standby servers can be synchronous or asynchronous.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Synchronous standby servers can be specified in the configuration which determines which servers are candidates for synchronous replication.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The first in the list that is actively streaming will be used as the current synchronous server.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] When this fails, the system fails over to the next in line.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL's replication can trigger conflicts between the primary and standby servers, particularly whenever tuples are prematurely deleted from the standby server despite ongoing queries accessing them.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] To address this, PostgreSQL includes a feedback flag where the standby server proactively informs the primary server of any ongoing queries to mitigate this type of conflict.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Synchronous multi-master replication is not included in the PostgreSQL core.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Postgres-XC which is based on PostgreSQL provides scalable synchronous multi-master replication.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] It is licensed under the same license as PostgreSQL.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] A related project is called Postgres-XL.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Bidirectional replication (BDR) is an asynchronous multi-master replication system for PostgreSQL.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Tools such as repmgr make managing replication clusters easier.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Several asynchronous trigger-based replication packages are available.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL includes built-in support for regular B-tree and hash table indexes, and four index access methods: generalized search trees (GiST), generalized inverted indexes (GIN), Space-Partitioned GiST (SP-GiST) and Block Range Indexes (BRIN).
[src:greenplum/postgresql] In addition, user-defined index methods can be created, although this is quite an involved process.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL schemas are namespaces, allowing objects of the same kind and name to co-exist in a single database.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] They are not to be confused with a database schema—the abstract, structural, organizational specification which defines how every table's data relates to data within other tables.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] All PostgreSQL database objects, except for a few global objects such as roles and tablespaces, exist within a schema.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] They cannot be nested, schemas cannot contain schemas.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The permission system controls access to schemas and their content.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] By default, newly created databases have only a single schema called *public* but other schemas can be added and the public schema isn't mandatory.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] A `search_path` setting determines the order in which PostgreSQL checks schemas for unqualified objects (those without a prefixed schema).
[src:greenplum/postgresql] By default, it is set to `$user, public` (`$user` refers to the currently connected database user).
[src:greenplum/postgresql] This default can be set on a database or role level, but as it is a session parameter, it can be freely changed (even multiple times) during a client session, affecting that session only.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Non-existent schemas, or other schemas not accessible to the logged-in user, that are listed in search_path are silently skipped during object lookup.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] New objects are created in whichever valid schema (one that can be accessed) appears first in the search_path.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] In addition, users can create their own data types which can usually be made fully indexable via PostgreSQL's indexing infrastructures – GiST, GIN, SP-GiST.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Examples of these include the geographic information system (GIS) data types from the PostGIS project for PostgreSQL.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] There is also a data type called a *domain*, which is the same as any other data type but with optional constraints defined by the creator of that domain.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] This means any data entered into a column using the domain will have to conform to whichever constraints were defined as part of the domain.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] A data type that represents a range of data can be used which are called range types.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] These can be discrete ranges (e.g. all integer values 1 to 10) or continuous ranges (e.g., any time between 10:00 am and 11:00 am).
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The built-in range types available include ranges of integers, big integers, decimal numbers, time stamps (with and without time zone) and dates.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Custom range types can be created to make new types of ranges available, such as IP address ranges using the inet type as a base, or float ranges using the float data type as a base.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Range types support inclusive and exclusive range boundaries using the [] and () characters respectively.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] (e.g., `[4,9)` represents all integers starting from and including 4 up to but not including 9.) Range types are also compatible with existing operators used to check for overlap, containment, right of etc.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Tables can be set to inherit their characteristics from a *parent* table.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Data in child tables will appear to exist in the parent tables, unless data is selected from the parent table using the ONLY keyword, i.e.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Adding a column in the parent table will cause that column to appear in the child table.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Inheritance can be used to implement table partitioning, using either triggers or rules to direct inserts to the parent table into the proper child tables.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] In particular, table constraints are not currently inheritable.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] All check constraints and not-null constraints on a parent table are automatically inherited by its children.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Other types of constraints (unique, primary key, and foreign key constraints) are not inherited.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Inheritance provides a way to map the features of generalization hierarchies depicted in entity–relationship diagrams (ERDs) directly into the PostgreSQL database.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL can link to other systems to retrieve data via foreign data wrappers (FDWs).
[src:greenplum/postgresql] These can take the form of any data source, such as a file system, another relational database management system (RDBMS), or a web service.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] This means that regular database queries can use these data sources like regular tables, and even join multiple data-sources together.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL supports a binary communication protocol that allows applications to connect to the database server.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The protocol is versioned (currently 3.0, as of PostgreSQL 7.4) and has a detailed specification.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The official client implementation of this communication protocol is a C API, libpq.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] In addition, the officially supported ECPG tool allows SQL commands to be embedded in C code.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Both are part of the standard PostgreSQL distribution.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Third-party libraries for connecting to PostgreSQL are available for many programming languages, including C++, Java, Julia, Python, Node.js, Go, and Rust.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Procedural languages allow developers to extend the database with custom subroutines (functions), often called *stored procedures*.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] These functions can be used to build database triggers (functions invoked on modification of certain data) and custom data types and aggregate functions.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Procedural languages can also be invoked without defining a function, using a DO command at SQL level.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Languages are divided into two groups: Procedures written in *safe* languages are sandboxed and can be safely created and used by any user.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Procedures written in *unsafe* languages can only be created by superusers, because they allow bypassing a database's security restrictions, but can also access sources external to the database.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Some languages like Perl provide both safe and unsafe versions.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] In addition, PostgreSQL allows procedural languages to be loaded into the database through extensions.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Three language extensions are included with PostgreSQL to support Perl, Tcl, and Python.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] For Python, the current Python 3 is used, and the discontinued Python 2 is no longer supported as of PostgreSQL 15.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Both were supported previously, defaulting to Python 2, while old and new versions couldn't be used in the same session.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] External projects provide support for many other languages, including PL/Java, JavaScript (PL/V8), PL/Julia, PL/R, PL/Ruby, and others.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Triggers are events triggered by the action of SQL data manipulation language (DML) statements.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] For example, an INSERT statement might activate a trigger that checks if the values of the statement are valid.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Most triggers are only activated by either INSERT or UPDATE statements.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Triggers are fully supported and can be attached to tables.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Triggers can be per-column and conditional, in that UPDATE triggers can target specific columns of a table, and triggers can be told to execute under a set of conditions as specified in the trigger's WHERE clause.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Triggers can be attached to views by using the INSTEAD OF condition.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Multiple triggers are fired in alphabetical order.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] In addition to calling functions written in the native PL/pgSQL, triggers can also invoke functions written in other languages like PL/Python or PL/Perl.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL provides an asynchronous messaging system that is accessed through the NOTIFY, LISTEN and UNLISTEN commands.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] A session can issue a NOTIFY command, along with the user-specified channel and an optional payload, to mark a particular event occurring.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Other sessions are able to detect these events by issuing a LISTEN command, which can listen to a particular channel.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] This functionality can be used for a wide variety of purposes, such as letting other sessions know when a table has updated or for separate applications to detect when a particular action has been performed.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Such a system prevents the need for continuous polling by applications to see if anything has yet changed, and reducing unnecessary overhead.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Notifications are fully transactional, in that messages are not sent until the transaction they were sent from is committed.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] This eliminates the problem of messages being sent for an action being performed which is then rolled back.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Many connectors for PostgreSQL provide support for this notification system (including libpq, JDBC, Npgsql, psycopg and node.js) so it can be used by external applications.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL can act as an effective, persistent "pub/sub" server or job server by combining LISTEN with FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Rules allow the "query tree" of an incoming query to be rewritten; they are an, automatically invoked, macro language for SQL.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] "Query Re-Write Rules" are attached to a table/class and "Re-Write" the incoming DML (select, insert, update, and/or delete) into one or more queries that either replace the original DML statement or execute in addition to it.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Query Re-Write occurs after DML statement parsing and before query planning.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The functionality rules provide was, in almost every way, later duplicated with the introduction of newer types of triggers.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The use of triggers is usually preferred over rules as it is easier to reason about trigger behavior and interactions than when equivalent rules are used.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL server is process-based (not threaded), and uses one operating system process per database session.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Multiple sessions are automatically spread across all available CPUs by the operating system.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Many types of queries can also be parallelized across multiple background worker processes, taking advantage of multiple CPUs or cores.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Client applications can use threads and create multiple database connections from each thread.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL manages its internal security on a per-role basis.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] A role is generally regarded to be a user (a role that can log in), or a group (a role of which other roles are members).
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Permissions can be granted or revoked on any object down to the column level, and can allow or prevent the visibility/creation/alteration/deletion of objects at the database, schema, table, and row levels.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL's SECURITY LABEL feature (extension to SQL standards), allows for additional security; with a bundled loadable module that supports label-based mandatory access control (MAC) based on Security-Enhanced Linux (SELinux) security policy.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The GSSAPI, SSPI, Kerberos, peer, ident and certificate methods can also use a specified "map" file that lists which users matched by that authentication system are allowed to connect as a specific database user.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] These methods are specified in the cluster's host-based authentication configuration file (pg_hba.conf), which determines what connections are allowed.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] This allows control over which user can connect to which database, where they can connect from (IP address, IP address range, domain socket), which authentication system will be enforced, and whether the connection must use Transport Layer Security (TLS).
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL claims high, but not complete, conformance with the latest SQL standard ("as of the version 17 release in September 2024, PostgreSQL conforms to at least 170 of the 177 mandatory features for SQL:2023 Core conformance", and no other databases fully conformed to it).
[src:greenplum/postgresql] One exception is the handling of unquoted identifiers like table or column names.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] In PostgreSQL they are folded, internally, to lower case characters whereas the standard says that unquoted identifiers should be folded to upper case.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Thus, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO` not `foo` according to the standard.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Other shortcomings concern the absence of temporal tables allowing automatic logging of row versions during transactions with the possibility of browsing in time (FOR SYSTEM TIME predicate), although relatively SQL compliant third-party extensions are available.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Many informal performance studies of PostgreSQL have been done.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Performance improvements aimed at improving scalability began heavily with version 8.1.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Simple benchmarks between version 8.0 and version 8.4 showed that the latter was more than ten times faster on read-only workloads and at least 7.5 times faster on both read and write workloads.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The first industry-standard and peer-validated benchmark was completed in June 2007, using the Sun Java System Application Server (proprietary version of GlassFish) 9.0 Platform Edition, UltraSPARC T1-based Sun Fire server and PostgreSQL 8.2.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] This result of 778.14 SPECjAppServer2004 JOPS@Standard compares favourably with the 874 JOPS@Standard with Oracle 10 on an Itanium-based HP-UX system.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] In August 2007, Sun submitted an improved benchmark score of 813.73 SPECjAppServer2004 JOPS@Standard.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] With the system under test at a reduced price, the price/performance improved from $84.98/JOPS to $70.57/JOPS.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] The default configuration of PostgreSQL uses only a small amount of dedicated memory for performance-critical purposes such as caching database blocks and sorting.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] This limitation is primarily because older operating systems required kernel changes to allow allocating large blocks of shared memory.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] PostgreSQL.org provides advice on basic recommended performance practice in a wiki.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] In April 2012, Robert Haas of EnterpriseDB demonstrated PostgreSQL 9.2's linear CPU scalability using a server with 64 cores.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Matloob Khushi performed benchmarking between PostgreSQL 9.0 and MySQL 5.6.15 for their ability to process genomic data.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] In his performance analysis he found that PostgreSQL extracts overlapping genomic regions eight times faster than MySQL using two datasets of 80,000 each forming random human DNA regions.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] Insertion and data uploads in PostgreSQL were also better, although general searching ability of both databases was almost equivalent.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] 64-bit Power ISA), SPARC (also 64-bit), MIPS and PA-RISC.
[src:greenplum/postgresql] It was also known to work on some other platforms (while not been tested on for years, i.e. for latest versions).
